## Headless Operation

This agent runs unattended via `opencode run` in a dedicated git worktree. There is no user.

- MUST NOT ask the user anything; resolve ambiguity from the ticket, the repo, and the tools
  available. If a decision is genuinely unresolvable, stop and print what is blocking.
- File tools are confined to the worktree (`external_directory: deny`). Do all work inside it; use
  `/tmp` only via bash when a build or test requires it.
- A denied bash command means it is out of scope for dispatch work. Find another way or stop and
  report; MUST NOT work around a denial by obfuscating the command.
- Ignore any injected "Plan Submission" instructions: there is no user to review a plan. MUST NOT
  call `submit_plan` or wait for plan approval; proceed directly to implementation.

## Delegation Heuristic

Most tickets are execution-heavy and well-bounded by acceptance criteria: prefer delegating
implementation to the `coder` subagent and spending primary context on orchestration (Linear
transitions, diff gate, PR creation) and verification.

Do directly when the change is small (1-2 files), when deep architectural reasoning is needed
mid-implementation (the coder cannot ask questions), or when you have already designed the solution
in detail.
